@node "Whatisit" "What is it?"
@{b}@{u}What is it?@{ub}@{uu}


LWPA is a simple particle animator for Lightwave 3d. It takes a user supplied object,
a source motion and some parameters, puts them all together and creates a scene which
can be loaded into Lightwave via the Load objects from scene button on the Objects
menu.


@{b}Requirements:@{ub}   68030 + 68882 or ABOVE with 512k or MORE!!
                AmigaDOS 2.0 or above,
                A big screen mode would be nice to fit the window
                in...

                Oh yeah, a copy of Lightwave 3.5 or above would be 
                handy... 


@{b}Recommended system:@{ub} 68040 or above with enough ram to run Lightwave!
                    Particle systems take a long time to create if
                    there are lots of particles to move around.
@endnode

@node "Functions" "Functions"
@{b}@{u}Functions@{ub}@{uu}


@{u}Required files@{uu}

@{b}Particle object@{ub} - lets you select the object to be used as the
                  particle in the system.
                  
                  You can type in the path or choose the file
                  via the get file gadget.
               
                  

@{b}Parent motion@{ub} -   This is the motion of the parent object. It
                  should be a Lightwave motion file. There does
                  not have to be more than one keyframe in it.
                  
                  All the particles will emanate from this point.
                  
                  Again, you can type in the path or choose the
                  location of the motion file.
                  
                  
                  

@{b}Target scene@{ub} -    This is the location of the scene to be generated.
                  This scene is the final product of LWPA and is the
                  thing that you load into Lightwave via the 
                  @{i}"Objects"@{ui} -> @{i}"Load from scene"@{ui} option.
                  
                  
                  

@{u}Particle options@{uu}

@{b}Particles@{ub} -       The total number of particles to include in the
                  scene.
                  
                  
                  

@{b}Particles per frame@{ub} - The number of particles to create every frame.
                      If this value x number of frames is greater
                      than the number of particles, the particles
                      will appear to "run out" too soon in the
                      generated scene. If this happens, just increase
                      the number of particles.
                      
                  

@{b}Particles lifespan@{ub} - If you need particles to live for a limited number
                     of frames then use this to set that value.
                     After the limit is reached then one of three things
                     will occur...
                  
                  
                     

@{b}End lifespan behaviour@{ub} - When a particle "runs out of life", then it will
                        either be: recycled, stop or be destroyed.
                        
                        Recycle means the particle will get created
                        again as a new particle when it dies.
                        
                        If Stop is selected then the particle will just
                        appear to freeze in the animation when it's
                        life expires.
                        
                        If Destroy is selected then the particle will
                        "disappear" when it's life expires. Actually
                        it's size will be set to 0 (so you can't see it).
                        
                        

@{b}Limited lifespan@{ub} - If you want the above two options then this should be
                   checked.
                   
                   

@{b}Particle velocity@{ub} - This is the velocity of each particle at creation time.
                    measured in meters per second.
                   
                    

@{b}Velocity variation@{ub} - Is the percentage variance in the creation time
                     velocity of each particle. This means that if you
                     want to add a bit a randomness to your particles
                     velocities, the value entered in this gadget 
                     (a percentage) will vary the velocity of each 
                     particle the range of the percentage.
                   
                     

@{b}Creation delay@{ub} - Use this option to put a delay on the appearance of each 
                 particle. Everything else will continue as normal but the
                 particle will be invisible until it reaches a certain age,
                 which you specify in this gadget. 
                 
                 This is useful for doing combined effects: say you were
                 trying to simulate the fire and the smoke from a rocket's
                 engine. You may create one scene for the fire, then you
                 could create another for the smoke; you'd want the
                 particles to emanate from the same place but you don't
                 want the smoke to get in the way of the fire, so you give
                 the smoke a creation delay...
                 
                 This is covered in a @{"tutorial" link "Tutorial1" 0}.
                 
                 There is also a check box for you to use if you don't
                 want to use creation delay.
                 
                 
                 

@{b}Start size, End size@{ub} - These two gadgets let you change the size of the
                       emitted particles from the start of their life
                       to the end.
                       
                       There is also a check box if you don't want to
                       bother with this option.
                 
                       

@{u}Scene options@{uu}

This brings up the standard Lighwave scene options, ie start frame,  end frame and
frame step - set as you please.

Note that the main window cannot be accessed while any of the sub-windows are open.
This is a problem which I am working on...




@{u}Emission options@{uu}

This is the most difficult bit to understand. These options specify the direction in
which the particles are emitted from the source.

@{b}Heading spread@{ub} is the top view of the emitter - the bigger the spread, the more angles
the particles are emitted from.

@{b}Heading angle@{ub} is the angle to offset the spread at. Imagine you set the spread at 180
degrees, so the particles get emitted at the front only (looking at the top view), if
you set the heading angle to 180 degrees the particles will only get emitted at the
back - ie. you just rotated the emission by 180 degrees.

@{b}Pitch spread@{ub} is the front view of the emitter - it is like a fan in that as you open a
fan it covers from 0 degrees to 180 degrees. If you imagine that the particles get
emitted from the bit of the fan you hold and go towards the edges - the more open the
fan, the more range of angles the particles can be emitted from. Pitch spread is
limited to 180 degrees max.


Particles are '.', pitch spread = ~ 90 degrees, angle = ~ 45 degrees.

                           . .
                        /.
                       /. .  .  .
                      /... . . .
                      \...   .     .
                       \.  .
                        \.
                           . .
 
 
                         I apologise for the poor ASCII diagrams!

@{b}Pitch angle@{ub} is like Heading angle but applied to the front view.


@{b}Oversampling@{ub} - use this option if you want particles created not specifically at each
keyframe but in between. This is usefull if you require a irregular stream of
particles.

@{u}Effect options@{uu}

@{b}Gravity@{ub} is the amount particles get pulled downwards, measured in meters per second
per second.



@{b}Elasticity@{ub} affects the amount the particles bounce. 100% elasticity means they will
bounce upto their "dropped from" height. 0 % means they won't bounce at all. 



If you would like the particles to "bounce" at the ground plane, then check the Bounce
at ground plane option.



@{b}Radial particle creation@{ub}

This is quite tricky to get your head round too... If you Imagine a closed pair of
compasses, as you open them one part stays on the page and the other moves away from
the centre. This is the parent motion. If you imagine that at each frame you draw a
circle with the compass - this circle represents the emitted particles, as you get
further down the parent's motion (amount compass is open by) you draw another circle
and thus create another circle of particles.

For this option to make sense your parent motion should not be static.

It is useful for creating radial effects such as shock waves, this is also covered in
a @{"tutorial" link "Tutorial2" 0}.




@{b}Linear path@{ub} - use this option if you have very simple particle motion ie. particles go
from a to b without any movement in between. It makes the creation of the scene
quicker. If you have gravity turned on with this option, it will look wrong in the
animation because there will be no gradual falling motion to the particles; they will
just go directly from start to end.

@{b}Non linear path@{ub} - use this if your particles need to do more complex motion. Use if
gravity is turned on.
@endnode

@node "Tutorial1" "Tutorial1"
@{b}@{u}Tutorial 1 - Rocket smoke and fire.@{ub}@{uu}

We will create the fire first of all.

Load up LWPA and apply the following settings:

                         choose the supplied fire.lwo as the
                         source particle, choose the supplied
                         rocketfire.mot as the source motion,
                         put the target scene anywhere you
                         like, call it "rocketfire.lws",

                         210 particles,
                         21 particles per frame,
                         10 frames particle lifespan,
                         end lifespan behaviour = recycle,
                         velocity = 40m/s
                         velocity variation = 20%
                         startsize = 40

                         120 frames

                         heading spread = 360
                         heading angle = 0
                         pitch spread = 20
                         pitch angle = -90

Now hit @{b}generate@{ub} and wait until the scene is generated and change these settings:

                         choose the supplied smoke.lwo
                         as the particle object, choose the
                         supplied rocketsmoke.mot as the
                         parent motion, put this scene
                         somewhere and call it
                         "rocketsmoke.lws"

                         840 particles,
                         7 particles per frame,
                         turn off limited lifespan,
                         velocity = 20 m/s
                         creation delay = 10 frames,
                         start size = 30
                         end size = 120

                         pitch spread = 30

Hit @{b}generate@{ub} and wait until this scene is finished.

Load both of these scenes into Lightwave using "Load from scene" on the "Objects"
menu. You may now render this sequence - I advise you  to choose a small render size
and not to use antialiasing unless you have a stupidly powerful  machine.

The result is the most realistic smoke / fire  simulation I have ever seen in
Lightwave. This is an example of the sort of thing that can be achieved using LWPA.

(If you don't have a really powerful machine /  all the time in the world, then you
can see the  pre-rendered version of this animation if you have an AVI player (yes, I
rendered on a PC...  Sorry!)).

Feel free to experiment.
@endnode

@node "Tutorial2" "Tutorial2"
@{b}@{u}Tutorial 2 - Explosion shock wave@{ub}@{uu}

First of all we need to create the parent motion.

Load up Lightwave and create a @{i}null object@{ui}, Switch to top view, Change the grid size
to @{b}5.0@{ub} by zooming out with the ']' key, Change the number of frames in this scene to
@{b}60@{ub}, Move the null object two grid units in the z direction and create a key at @{b}60@{ub},
Save this motion as "@{b}radialmotion.mot@{ub}".

Now we need to go to @{i}LWPA@{ui} to create our shock wave.

Choose the supplied "@{b}fire2.lwo@{ub}" as the parent object. Choose the motion we just
created ("@{b}radialmotion.mot@{ub}")  as the parent motion, Choose a sensible location for the
target scene - not the RAM disk unless you have about 5Mb of free RAM, Enter @{b}3000@{ub} as
the number of particles, Enter @{b}300@{ub} as the number of particles per frame, Particle
life-span should be set at @{b}10@{ub} frames (limited life-span should be set), End particle
behaviour should be recycle, Particle velocity should be set at @{b}0.05m/s@{ub}, Use @{b}20%@{ub} as
the velocity variation, Particle start size should be set at @{b}0.1@{ub}, Start frame should
be set to @{b}1@{ub}, end frame at @{b}60@{ub}, The most important bit is to check the @{b}Radial particle
creation@{ub} checkbox, Heading spread needs to be set at @{b}10@{ub}, angle at @{b}90@{ub}, Pitch spread
needs to be set at @{b}90@{ub}, angle at @{b}0@{ub}.

Now hit generate and wait about a day! (I am not joking!) - If you don't have time to
wait a day, then change the number of particles to a lesser value - try 300 with 30
particles per frame.

Once everything is created load up @{i}Lightwave@{ui} and load in the scene we have just
created.

You will probably want to change the camera position - it will be directly facing the
explosion and you wont see the 3d ring of fire. Try a position that puts the camera
above the ring, rotate the camera so it is looking down at the ring (try a frame
number of 40 to see the ring) and key the camera at 0.

Now you are ready to render a frame (or the entire thing), choose camera settings as
you feel fit - I suggest lowres (one frame took about 7 minutes on a p100).

If you don't have the patients to wait for the entire animation you can look at the
pre-rendered version "shockwave.avi" if you have an AVI player.

Feel free to experiment. Good luck!
@endnode

